   <xocs:rawtext>Volume 148, number 4  CHEMICAL PHYSICS LEiTERS  15 July 1983  THE CHANGE OF X-RAY ABSORPTION NEAR EDGE STRUCFURE  IN SOLID AND SOLUTION    Mitsuru SANO  Department of Chemistry, College of General Education, Nagoya University, Nagoya 464, Japan    Received 4 March 1988; in final form 28 April 1988         XANES spectra of Co complexes have been measured in solid and solution. The spectra in aqueous solutions were found to  remain unchanged at different concentrations, while they were found to differ from those in crystals. These findings suggest that  the spectral change does not originate from a long-range effect of the counter ions surrounding the complex ion but from a change  in the geometrical and electronic structure of the coordination sphere. The present study shows the origin of the counter-ion effect  and also the usefulness of XANES as a sensitive probe for distortions of local structure.   In a recent paper [1], we reported that systematic  measurements of Co K-edge XANES for Co (III)  complexes showed counter-ion effect for  [Co(NH3)6]X3 (X=Cl, Br, and!). [Co(NH5)6]C15  and [Co (NH3 )6 J I~ gave only one resonance at an  energy about 17 and 19 eV higher than that of the  main peak B (see fig. 1), respectively, while  z  LU  H  z    LU  H    -1  LU  ENERGY (eV)  Fig. 1. XANES spectra of Co(NOs)r6H2O (solid),  Co(ClO4)2~6H2O (solid), CoSO4 7H20 (solid) and 0.2 M CoSO4  and 0.05 M Co(C104)2 aqueous solutions.  [Co (NH3) 6] Br3 showed two resonances at about 15  and 21 eV from the main peak. This counter-ion ef-  fect will be discussed in detail in the present paper.   There can be two interpretations for the origin of  these resonances. One is that an electron excited into  the continuum state is virtually trapped within the  cage (potential bather) made of counter ions sur-  rounding the complex ion. The other is that an elec-  tron is trapped within the ligand potential bather  which is strongly affected by the electronic and geo-  metrical structure of the complex. In this note,  XANFS spectra of cobalt complexes are compared  between crystals and aqueous solutions and the or-  igin of the counter-ion effect is discussed.   The Co K-edge spectra were measured with the  EXAFS facilities at BL- 1 OB of KEK-PF [2]. Ml  spectra have been normalized to give an edge jump  of 1.0.   Fig. 1 shows the XANES spectra of Co2~ ions in  crystals and aqueous solutions which have the same  [Co (H2O)6 2+ chromophore [3]. The spectra show  differences at band B between crystals with different  counter anions and between a crystal and the solu-  tion of the same compound. However, the spectra of  solutions of different concentrations are almost  identical. The known equilibrium constants for  the ion association ([Co(H2O)6]2~ +X ~  [Co(H2O)6]2~ X) showed that the ion associa-  tion species, [Co (H20 ) 612+  SO~   predominates in  0 009-26 14/88/$ 03.50   Elsevier Science Publishers B.V.  (North-Holland Physics Publishing Division)  331   7700 75Q  volume 14g, number 4  CHEMICAL PHYSICS LEiTERS  15 July 1988  0.2 M CoSO4 solution [4], whereas the free aqua-  cobalt(I1) ion [Co(H2O)6]2~ predominates in 0.05  M Co (004)2 solution [5]. If the counter-ion effect  observed in crystals originated from a long-range in-  fluence of the counter ions, the two spectra of the  aqueous solutions should be different. Thus the ex-  perimental results allow us to infer that the counter-  ion effect originates from geometrical and electronic  distortion of the coordination sphere but not from a  long-range influence of counter ions.   The XANES of [Co(NH3)6]3  moieties in the  solid state and in aqueous solution are shown in fig.  2, in which two features are noted: the first is the  change in the intensity of band A at the edge of the  spectra from chloride to bromide and from crystal to  solution. The second is the manifestation of the  counter-ion effect in band C for [Co (NH3 )6 ] Cl3 and  [Co (NH3)6]Br3, in contrast to the little difference  between the spectra of solutions with different  concentrations.   According to conductance studies [6] on aqueous  [Co (NH3) 6]  Bc solutions, the free [Co (NH3)6] ~  and the ion pair [Co(NH,)6]3~~Br are the pre-  dominant species in 0.01 M and 0.05 M solutions,  respectively. The similarity between the spectra for  the two solutions demonstrates that ion-pair for-  mation does not contribute to the counter-ion effect.  I-  z  LU  LU  LU  Fig. 2. XANES spectra of [Co(NH3)6lCl3 (solid),  [Co(NH3)6]Br3 (solid), and 0.01 Mand 0.05 M [Co(NH3)6]Br3  aqueous solutions.  However, the strong interaction between the com-  plex ion and its counter ions in solid causes a change  in the geometrical arrangement and charge distri-  bution within the complex ion; e.g. the Co N bond  lengths are 1.955 1.983 A for [Co(NH3)6]Cl3 [7].  Such a distortion of the complex ion in the crystal  will cause a change in the electronic state and thus  a change in the spectrum. The interaction between  the ions in the ion pair is likely to be very weak, re-  sulting in no significant change in the geometrical  and electronic structure.   The results described in the preceding paragraphs  are consistent with the findings of Bianconi et al. [8]  and of Sham [9]. The former authors interpreted Fe   K XANES spectra of [Fe(CN)6]3 and  [Fe (CN )6] ~ by means of multiple-scattering cal-  culations and considered that differences in struc-  tural modification due to differences in the charge of  the complex ion resulted in the difference in the ob-  served XANES spectrum. The Pt LLII XANES spec-  tra of K2PtCI4 crystal and aqueous solution were  studied by Sham, who concluded that the difference  between the crystal and solvation spectra is ascrib-  able to the difference in environment; the Pt atoms  in the crystal lie linearly with a Pt Pt distance of 4.1  A, whereas each Pt atom in solution exists in a dis-  crete [PtCl4 2~ Our present findings, together with  the previous ones cited above, demonstrate that  XANES spectra can be used as a sensitive probe for  a slight distortion of local structure which are not de-  tected by EXAFS. The counter-ion effect was hardly  observed in solutions, but was clearly shown, indi-  cating the distortion of the complex ion in crystals.     We thank Professor Hideo Yamatera for his useful  discussion and his encouragement. We also acknowl-  edge a Grant-in-Aid (No. 61470044) for Scientific  Research from the Ministry of Education, Science  and Culture. This work has been performed under  the approval of the Photon Factory Program Advi-  sory Committee (Proposal No. 86015).        References    [11 M. Sano, tobe published.  [21 H. Oyanagi, T. Matsushita, M. Ito and H. Kuroda, KEK Re-  port 83-10 (1983).  ENERGY (eV)  332  Volume 148, number 4  CHEMICAL PHYSICS LEiTERS  15 July 1988  [3] H. Ohtaki, T. Yamaguchi and M. Maeda, Bull. Chem. Soc.  Japan 49 (1976)701.  [4] H. Yokoyama and H. Yaniatera, Bull. Chem. Soc. Japan 54  (1981) 2286.  [5] Z. LibusandT. Sadowska,J. Phys. Chem. 73(1969)3229.  [61 H. Yokoyama, private communication;  S. Katayama and R. Tamamushi, Bull. Chem. Soc. Japan 41  (1968) 606.  El] G.J. Kruger and E.C. Reynhardt, Acta Cryst. B 34 (1978)  915.  [8] A. Bianconi, M. Dell Ariccia, P.J. Durham and J.B. Pendry,  Phys.Rev.B26 (1982) 6502.  [9] T.K. Sham, J. Chem. Phys. 84 (1986) 7054.  333  ence of the counter ions, the two spectra of the  aqueous solutions should be different. Thus the ex-  perimental results allow us to infer that the counter-  ion effect originates from geometrical and electronic  distortion of the coordination sphere but not from a  long-range influence of counter ions.   The XANES of [Co(NH3)6]3  moieties in the  solid state and in aqueous solution are shown in fig.  2, in which two features are noted: the first is the  change in the intensity of band A at the edge of the  spectra from chloride to bromide and from crystal to  solution. The second is the manifestation of the  